post_text: Thanks for the update Buena Park Police Department!
shared_text:
Buena Park Police Department
September 10 at 3:35 PM ·

The outdoor odor wafting through Buena Park and surrounding areas is NOT from natural gas. According to the Los Angeles County Fire Department, the odor is the result of a chemical spill at a construction site near the City of Compton. A hazmat team has responded and according to officials, the spill is under control. Officials report the odor is harmless, although individuals who are sensitive to odors should consider staying indoors until the odor completely dissipates.
If you ever suspect a natural gas leak, immediately evacuate the area and, from a safe location, call SoCalGas® at 1-800-427-2200.

Beginning on TUESDAY, SEPTEMBER 8th - CESD Food Services will be providing drive thru meals for FREE to all children 18 and under again at Danbrook, Walter Knott and San Marino.

Thanks to the support of thousands of school districts around the country, we were able to communicate the true need of meal availability for our children and in turn, the USDA has agreed to extend the Free Meal Service until December 2020.

Please be sure to share the news with our students, families, neighbors, and anyone else that may have children to come on by!

post_text:
Dear Centralia Families and Staff:

This week, the Orange County School Board of Education has again made news headlines with a decision to sue the Governor of California over his most recent set of guidance for schools.

It is important for our community to know that the Centralia Elementary School District is governed by its own Board of Education, who are in no way directed by the OC School Board. The CESD Board remain committed to opening schools for in-person instruction as soon as it is safe to do so, following appropriate guidance.

The Centralia Elementary School District Board of Education is scheduled to meet this coming Wednesday, August 5th. The agenda for the meeting will be posted by Friday evening.

Transitional Kindergarten (TK)/Kindergarten Registration for the 2020-21 school year continues during the current school dismissal- ONLINE! If you have a child that will be TK or Kindergarten age, please enroll NOW for priority spaces.

We are asking all current CESD Preschool students to enroll online to register for TK or Kindergarten. Click http://ow.ly/m54P50zFMX7 to begin registration! Please check the District website for additional information: http://ow.ly/jq9J50zFMXa

Current CESD TK students DO NOT need to enroll online for Kindergarten; current TK students will be enrolled in their school of residence for the upcoming school year unless they have an approved Intradistrict Transfer to attend another school.

Questions? Call 714-228-3141 for eligibility and information.

post_text: We will definitely be tuning in for Canine Chronicles with Adam! Thanks Buena Park Police Department!
shared_text:
Buena Park Police Department
March 26 at 8:51 AM ·

****ATTENTION KIDS!****

Join us tomorrow, Friday March 27, 2020 at 2 pm for our first ever Canine Chronicles, featuring K9 Adam and his partner Officer Boyer. Adam and Boyer will read a children’s book over Facebook and Instagram live, so you don’t even have to leave your homes and can practice social distancing.

After the reading, Adam and Boyer will answer a few questions the children may have. Questions can be submitted ahead of time via direct message and live questions will be taken as well.

We look forward to seeing you (virtually)!

#BPPD #BuenaParkPD #CanineChronicles #Read #books #children #AllAboutTheKids #K9

post_text:
Buena Terra is participating in a UC Davis grant funded initiative aimed at closing the STEM opportunity gap for girls, aged 10-12. The mission is to instill girls with the courage, confidence, and tools needed to stay the course and become tomorrow’s STEM leaders.
Buena Terra is offering 10, two-hour session courses to our 5th and 6th grade girls using STEM discovery kits provided by "SNAP THE GAP". Eligible mentors will be paired with a student and participate in 20 hours of in-person mentoring over 10 weeks. At the conclusion of the program, Buena Terra will host a Family Showcase at 5:00 p.m.
Buena Terra's "SNAP THE GAP" Team is seeking volunteer female mentors to help support discovery, foster confidence, and encourage invention in STEM. Mentoring sessions are from 2:30 to 4:30pm on 3/3, 3/10, 3/17, 3/31, 4/7, 4/14, 4/21, 4/28, 5/5, and 5/12.
If you are interested in sharing your time and skills with our future female science leaders, please apply at http://ow.ly/qqZI50yt18H

post_text:
Happy Halloween! Remember, be safe out there. Some helpful tips include:
-Remember reflective tape for costumes and trick-or-treat bags.
-Carry a cell phone for quick communication.
-Remain on well-lit streets and always use the sidewalk.
-If no sidewalk is available, walk at the far edge of the roadway facing traffic.
-Never cut across yards or use alleys.
-Only cross the street as a group in established crosswalks . Never cross between parked cars or out of driveways.
-Don't assume the right of way. Motorists may have trouble seeing trick-or-treaters. Just because one car stops, doesn't mean others will
Be safe, and make sure that you get some rest - we will see you all at school on Friday November 1!

post_text: Today is the 20th #LightsOnAfterschool day! Lights On is an annual event to shine attention to the value that after-school programs provide families and the community. Centralia is #CESDProud to have an amazing after-school (and before school) program at each of our school sites. After-school programs are proven to keep kids safe, engaged and provide peace of mind for working families. Centralia's programs not only offer educational support, but engaging activities and a warm meal daily. We are thankful to our Child Development staff for making sure the after-school lights are always on for our families!

post_text: At San Marino Elementary on September 17, 2019, the Daughters of the American Revolution (DAR), the Sons of the American Revolution (SAR), and the Liberty Patriots presented an assembly for the fifth and sixth grade classes in celebration of the United States Constitution. The SAR presented the colors, then students participated in the Pledge of Allegiance and singing the Star Spangled Banner. A slide presentation provided history and facts about our Constitution, while actors portraying Thomas Jefferson, Betsy Ross, and James Madison brought this history to life for our San Marino scholars.

post_text:
Danbrook School Principal Erasmo Garcia and Teacher Susanne Shapiro Hoglund, along with District Superintendent Norma Martinez and Assistant Superintendents Scott Martin and Kristine Cvar and Board Trustee Art Montez joined in the celebration of the making of a wish of one of our young scholars.

Our young scholar was granted a wish by the Make a Wish Foundation. To make his dream come true, the entire City of Anaheim, the Anaheim Police Department, the Anaheim Police Association, Knott’s Berry Farm, John’s Incredible Pizza, the Ducks and the Angels joined in helping our student become a superhero for the day! He battled the “bad guys” from one end of town to another, all with the support of great volunteers from these many organizations. The event concluded with a ceremony in which Anaheim Mayor Sidhu thanked our little guy for saving our city! Dream come true!

Welcome to our new Common Sense Schools! What is a Common Sense School you ask? A school earning Common Sense Badge certification is a symbol of that school's dedication to helping students think critically and use technology responsibly to learn, create, and to be safe responsible digital citizens. Way to go San Marino, Los Coyotes, Dysinger, Miller, Raymond Temple and Buena Terra!
Creating tomorrow's best cyber-practices today is yet another way we are #CESDStrong!

post_text:
After an extensive analysis of student data for every public school in California, Educational Results Partnership (ERP) and the Campaign for Business and Education Excellence (CBEE) awarded Dysinger Elementary School as a 2018-2019 Honor Roll School for being “ a clear leader in getting students to grade-level and beyond.”

Along with 6 other Centralia Elementary School district schools, the 2018 - 2019 Honor Roll recognizes demonstrated high levels of student academic achievement, improvement in achievement over time, and reduction in achievement gaps. Congratulations to our Dysinger school community for the dedication to evidence based instructional practices, which include clear, specific learning objectives aligned to college and career readiness. We are truly #CESDStrong!

Thank you to the Ducks & all of their partners 👏
Check out our story for more from this morning!

post_text: Every month Los Coyotes holds a student-led assembly. This past month our student leaders chose to honor our parking lot volunteers naming them LC Superheros! post_text: Centralia Elementary School was awarded the Fresh Fruit and Vegetables Program (FFVP) Grant offered by the U.S. Department of Agriculture Food Nutrition Services. The FFVP promotes fresh fruits and vegetables in high need elementary schools throughout the United Stated. Students at Centralia and Danbrook Elementary Schools are offered these fruits and vegetables during our morning recess break. Students have enjoyed strawberries, sweet peppers, and so much more! Thank you to our district’s Food Services department for making this happen for us, the students have enjoyed their fruits and veggies! #theplacetoBee #CESDStrong

post_text:
Centralia School District is excited to partner with @CalOptima and @CommunityHealthInitiativeofOrangeCounty (CHIOC) to provide health resources and events for the community’s families.

On Sept. 7th, CHIOC provided “Know Your Benefits” presentations at Danbrook School and will offer a duplicate session on Sept. 27th at Centralia School. On Oct. 4th, we will be providing a District-wide Health Benefits Enrollment Fair at Centralia School to directly assist families in enrolling in Medi-Cal and other services, and to provide additional presentations by CalOptima.

It is our goal to provide our parents and guardians with knowledge and resources to empower them to become stronger supports for their families.

For questions about the events, contact the Parent and Student Engagement Dept at 714-228-3141.

post_text: Missing information from the school? Trying to read the crumpled up flyer from the bottom of your scholar's backpack? The days of the overstuffed backpack are coming to an end, thanks to Peachjar! Centralia Elementary School District is excited to get closer to launching Peachjar e-flyers district-wide. Starting September 17, you will be able to read and respond to flyers - from your mobile device or computer! It's simple, better for the environment and makes information from the schools more accessible. Be on the look out for the email coming to you soon from Peachjar about this awesome program. Want to know more now? Click to read all about it! http://ow.ly/EQQz50vWVWj

post_text: To promote literacy and to put quality books into the hands of Buena Terra students, the Birthday Book Club was created. This PTA sponsored event at Buena Terra Elementary provides every child a book for their birthday. At the end of their birthday month, students can come and pick a book of their choice. Proceeds from the school site's Scholastic Book Fairs provides books for our Birthday Book Club. For the past two years, Mr. and Mrs. Beltran have chaired the committee. We are thankful to our parent committees for their support. Buena Terra believes in promoting a love of reading by putting quality literature into the hands of our students.#CESDStrong

post_text: On August 26th, Centralia Elementary School officially opened its new Parent Center in Room 21. Ms. Irene Aragon, Centralia School Community Liaison, welcomes school parents and staff, as well as district administrators to the opening. Several parents listened to a detailed presentation on the purpose and function of the Parent Center. The Center will host parent workshops, classes and volunteering opportunities. We welcome our community to visit the Center and learn what valuable resources are available to our families. #theplacetoBee #CESDStrong

It's the end of the last Monday of summer - things are really moving now! Classrooms are set up, rosters are being finalized and those special final touches are being added to school sites. We are nearly ready to start the 19/20 School Year! We are so excited to see all our Centralia scholars bright and early on Wednesday, August 7.
Remember - class lists will be posted on each school website August 6 at 5:00 pm., and staff will be on hand the first few days to help guide students to their new classrooms.
